In Antwerp 28 maij
Lillo - Jean de Grand
mons. gelieft te verclaren int beurtschip van Cornelis Jacops - op Rott
Een pack als imargine inhoudende 34 stuxkens row ongeblijck lijnwaert
kosten £285 vlaems doch hoe veel Ellen daer sijn en kan niet weten
vermidts deselve hier p transit passeren, eghter dat noodigh sijnde
te weten soude geen moglijck heijt begeiren, soo gelieft het noodigh daer
voorte besorgen ende mij p eerste laten weten wat onkosten daer op
N.1 vallen, de welke ul beneffens de leste gepasseirde cassen ten danck
sal rembourseren, terwijlen

23 maij 1681
segers van Enguien waermede
Mons. Jan B Masson
Mons. selon l'ordre de mons. veraghteren J'ay envoyez a la maison
mortuure de fen mons dunont 2 perpetuanes noir, quils ont renvoyez
a cause que les draps que vous demande ne seront pas prest que dans 3 ppmaines
alors ie vous envoyerez avee si vre grace neles demand pas plus tempse
entre temp ie commence la fabrique de draps que mons demont aen
en fin sice vous peu seriire enquelque chose commande bibremente
13 maij 1681
London Henry Maynard -
P. the 21: curitt wrott you what was needfull, sence wee have understood
that the branden bourgh capers or priuatiers have taken severall binlanders, as
well that come from England as hollant butt as yett wee know nott henames
of the ships m. onely that 5 were brought up att duynkerque the iy curitt
this day wee receaved the mindayes letters from london, by which m. Hem
wrott to Roosendael that Roow lamerd was weighting for a furre wind
so I hope you have the news fore now of what past & that said lamere is
detained where for please to take out our goods & schip them for Rotterdam
or flushing also what Elce is ready or a providing, for I will venterno
more in spanish vessels till that affaire be advisted whilst intrim
I supose some english ship will bealoading for ostend & remaine
In Antwap 23 maij 168160
Lille Richd. Southell
Sr. sence I wrott to you on the 13: curitt non from you this onely for couete
to the inclosed letter, which I send by way of yd parts for Englend to m maynard
which pray expediate pr. first I do not doubt butt that you heard what the brandens
burgh commissioners have take & brought up att duynker que, which doth quite ruun
our trade, for by that here is very sittle to do, & mony almost no more to be had
50 finde that I am constraimed to do less how things go with you shall be glad to know
whilst I hope you are well & all freinds & remaine with kinde saluts
Brussel Bern: vanderklooster
In Antwerpen 23 maij 1681
Monsr. in gevolghde ul schrijven van 19 deser soo hebbe de 34 stux lijnwaet
doen herpacken in een pack het selve germerckt SN1 ende gesonden p
Cornelis Jacobs beurt schip op Rost A monsr Jacques Angier om te volgen
d'ordre van mons segers van Enguien, soo haest de Rek becomen vant
geen op sort Austrewel & lillo, betaelt heeft sal dan alles samen voegen &
Aen ul toesenden gisteren nae middagh hebbe het gelt voor ul bewijs ontfang
te weten ƒ 350 daer af ƒ2 soo hebbe in ul rek gestelt ƒ348: waer in ul
voorder kan dienen gelieft liberlijk te commandeeren
Brussel Joan Jacobs
Mons. Den ul van 22 deser wel ontfangen wegens het gementioneert sack
lakens & is noch niet gekomen, en nu met de confusie daer der branden
bourghers cappers en wet niet ofte het selve niet en sal sijn in een van
de genomen schepen want tot duynkerque 5 bijlanders sijn opgebroght
waer van wij de naemen noch nieten wete daer af morgen meerder
be schet verwacht & aen ul sal laten weten terwijlen nae groet blijve
London Abram vivian
In Antwerp 24 maij 1681
Sr. my last to you was on the 25:t curitt sence recd. yd of 9 ditto in which I observe
that itt is with yd laces customers, iust as itt goeths dayly here with our cloth
customers which if wee would beleave, would make itt a peare that I sell 5 a 6 p
dearer then any other, nay sweere that they buy fine northrens for 5 2 & 53 stuvers
an ell from other, andyett they do not part butt they give 55„ 56 a 57 s anell
thought itt cost a world of words to persuade them to itt, because they are so much
inclined & ised to be for their owne intrest, which I am apt to be leave of yd also
& there fore you must not hearken to any of such discourses one thing g observe
that yd people will have cours goods & a great shew, butt do not mindeacutions
thingh, which I say because I know very well what sorts mr. scawen hath, for
I bought some fore him & never had one word of complaints, nay that I buycheap
can Demonstrate you bj that viz after I sended away yd last packett, there were
4 a 5 peeces over which I tought to have added, butt not finding them penny worth
to my minde, kept them here and ordered one of my lace women to sell y und
towne which she did & I gott by them so Jean not com prehend how itt
should bepossible, that what I send to you, should not prove better, what laced
I buy have not from one hand, nay from 6 butt from many for now I am
so well accouainted with the worck women, that bring ym to marketts that
there is herdely one butt she knows mee as well att Brussell, Helst, loven
meggelen & incloosters, as here amonghst others one which sells for many
thousans guilders to mr. taylors partier, as the shewd mee here self: neeter
novertheles if ever Iamable to do any thing, shall now end cavour) and in case
what I shall now send will not do I shall be content you dedist so then
shall prepare 2 packetts to yd dircction and one packett from peece to peece
to the rection of m. scawer that so you may see by which manner
you finde the best incorrigement to continue there is no apercance here of
a yackt comming, so will send for newport as soone as ready of or the broad lace
I remember I sent you one, and markett y with a note because itt was loohed upon
here to be so good apenni worth itt was of a plaine ground, if itt be that you complaine
